    content: "FAA has issued a ground stop for American Airlines flights across the United States causing major delays for thousands of travelers. Here's everything you need to know if you're affected. What Happened: On June 14, 2026, the FAA ordered a nationwide ground stop for all American Airlines flights due to a telecommunications issue at the airline's operations center. The ground stop was active for approximately 2 hours affecting departures across all American Airlines hubs including Dallas/Fort Worth (DFW), Charlotte (CLT), Chicago O'Hare (ORD), Miami (MIA), Los Angeles (LAX), Philadelphia (PHL), Phoenix (PHX), and New York JFK/LGA. Current Status: The ground stop has been lifted as of the latest update. However, residual delays are expected throughout the day as the airline works to recover its schedule. American Airlines has issued a travel waiver allowing affected passengers to rebook without change fees. Affected Airports: The ground stop impacted all American Airlines mainline and American Eagle regional flights systemwide. Delta, United, Southwest, and other carriers were not affected. If you're flying today, check if your American Airlines flight is delayed using the American Airlines app or website. Passenger Rights: Under DOT regulations, passengers affected by FAA ground stops are entitled to: full refund if the flight is canceled and you choose not to rebook, rebooking on the next available American Airlines flight without additional charges, meal vouchers if the delay exceeds 3 hours (at the airport), hotel accommodation if the delay requires an overnight stay (at the airline's discretion). If your American Airlines flight is delayed by 3+ hours, you may also be eligible for compensation depending on the specific circumstances. How to Check Your Flight: Use the American Airlines app, visit aa.com and enter your flight number, call American Airlines reservations at 1-800-433-7300, check your flight status on the FAA website, or follow @AmericanAir on Twitter/X for real-time updates. What to Do If You're at the Airport: Stay near your gate for announcements, speak to an American Airlines gate agent about rebooking options, check the AA app for automatic rebooking, and if your delay is significant, ask for meal and hotel vouchers before leaving the airport. For passengers traveling to/from FIFA 2026 host cities, note that American Airlines is an official partner of FIFA and operates additional flights to host cities during the World Cup. If you're flying to see a FIFA 2026 match, contact American Airlines immediately to rebook and ensure you don't miss kickoff.",
